In statistics, the term **population** refers to the `entire group of individuals, items, or observations` that a researcher is interested in studying. It is the `complete set` from which a sample may be drawn for analysis and conclusions.

---

### Definition

A **population** is the whole set of elements (people, objects, events, etc.) that possess a common characteristic defined for a particular statistical study.

---

### Examples of Population

| Population Type       | Example                              |
| --------------------- | ------------------------------------ |
| Human Population      | All students in a school             |
| Object Population     | All books in a library               |
| Event Population      | All accidents on a highway in a year |
| Data-Based Population | All test scores in a national exam   |

---

### Types of Population

| Type                    | Description                                                | Example                         |
| ----------------------- | ---------------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------- |
| **Finite Population**   | Has a countable number of elements                         | Number of students in a class   |
| **Infinite Population** | Cannot be counted or has endless elements                  | Number of stars in the universe |
| **Target Population**   | The population about which information is required         | All citizens eligible to vote   |
| **Sampled Population**  | The portion of the population actually `observed or studied` | Students selected for a survey  |

---

### Importance of Defining Population

* Defines the scope
* Guides sample selection
* Affects accuracy


### Conclusion

Understanding the concept of **population** is essential in statistics as it sets the foundation for data collection and analysis. A well-defined population ensures that the results of a `study are valid, reliable, and applicable` to the real world.
